  title: C# Adventures
  textDataArray:
  - '<size=45>Get User Input</size>

    You have already learned that <#F2B84B>hero.Say()</color>
    is used to output (print) values. Now we will use <#F2B84B>hero.ReadString(),
    hero.ReadInt(), hero.ReadDouble() </color> to get user input.



    The following
    examples apply the three input methods for string, int, and double data types:'
  - "<size=45>String Example</size>\r\n<#538C51>// Type your username and press enter</color>\r\nhero.Say(\"Enter
    username:\");\r\n\r\n<#538C51>// Create a string variable and get user input
    from the keyboard and store it in the variable\r</color>\nstring userName = hero.ReadString();\r\n\r\n<#538C51>//
    Print the value of the variable (userName), which will display the input value\r</color>\nhero.Say(\"Username
    is: \" + userName);"
  - "<size=45>Int Example</size>\r\n<#538C51>// Type your age and press enter</color>\r\nhero.Say(\"Enter
    age:\");\r\n\r\n<#538C51>// Create a int variable and get user input from the
    keyboard and store it in the variable\r</color>\nint age = hero.ReadInt();\r\n\r\n<#538C51>//
    Print the value of the variable (age), which will display the input value\r</color>\nhero.Say(\"Your
    Age is: \" + age);"
  - "<size=45>Double Example</size>\r\n<#538C51>// Type your height in centimeter
    and press enter</color>\r\nhero.Say(\"Enter height:\");\r\n\r\n<#538C51>// Create
    a double variable and get user input from the keyboard and store it in the variable\r</color>\ndouble
    height= hero.ReadDouble();\r\n\r\n<#538C51>// Print the value of the variable
    (height), which will display the input value\r</color>\nhero.Say(\"Your Height
    in centimeter is: \" + height);"
  - "<size=45>Double Example</size>\r\n<#538C51>// Type your height in centimeter
    and press enter</color>\r\nhero.Say(\"Enter height:\");\r\n\r\n<#538C51>// Create
    a double variable and get user input from the keyboard and store it in the variable\r</color>\ndouble
    height= hero.ReadDouble();\r\n\r\n<#538C51>// Print the value of the variable
    (height), which will display the input value\r</color>\nhero.Say(\"Your Height
    in centimeter is: \" + height);"
  - 'NOTE: the <#F2B84B>hero.ReadString()</color> method returns a string.  Therefore,
    you cannot get information from another data type, such as <#F2B84B>int</color>.
    Be sure to use the correct input method for a certain data type.


    hero.ReadString()
    //returns a string data type

    hero.ReadInt() //returns a int data type

    hero.ReadDouble()
    //returns a double data type


    Incorrect use of these methods will throw
    an error.'
